Abstract¶

Write your abstract

Introduction¶

It has long been known that the Arctic region is particular sensitive to global warming (Collins et al., 2013). In a warming climate will the sea ice decrease and larger areas of open water will follow an increas in organic aerosol uptake. Aerosols (organic or anthropogenic) can affect the Earth climate through interaction with solar radiation and clouds. Continuous AOD measurements from Sunphotometers distributed over the globe can give an idea about the distribution of aerosols in the atmosphere. This measurements are sparse in the Arctic and represent the AOD distribution only for a small area. With the lanch of satellites it is possible to retrieve global estimates of aerosol optical depth (AOD). Cloud free daily data can be used to reanalyse the AOD in a finer grid scale and use it to validate global climate model performance to predict the changing climate more accurately. Glantz et al., 2014 analysed the AOD in the Svalbard area. They compared Moderate Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer (MODIS) Aqua retrievals of AOD to Sunphotometer measurements from Svalbard. The study showed that the the Svalbard region undergoes a seasonal cycle with higher AOD during spring and a low AOD during summer. The remote sensing data is then used to examine the AOD generation of global climate models, represented in the Coupled Model Intercomparison Project 5 (CMIP5). The results showed an underestimation of AOD during spring and overestimation during summer by the CMIP5 models against the remote sensing data on the preiod 1980-2004.

In the presented study nine years of Modern-Era Retrospective analysis for Research and Applications 2 (MERRA2) satellite reanalysis is compared to ground-based Sunphotometer AOD measurements in the Arctic. Thereafter, are climate model simulations from CMIP6 examined in comparison to MERRA2 satellite reanalysis over 34 years. The following questions are addressed:

  1. How representative are MERRA2 satellite reanalysis in comparison to the ground-based AOD observations in the Arctic?
  2. How accurately do global climate model simulate the seasonal cycle of AOD for the Arctic?

Section 2.1 and Section 2.2 contains the code to read the observational data from the Sunphotmeters and the MERRA2 satellite reanalysis in the Arctic region, respectively. Section 2.3 consists of the code for finding the AOD at 550nm in the CMIP6 models and their ensembles.

Ground-based, satellite reanalysis and CMIP model data¶

Global climate models are essential to study future climate changes of aerosols and clouds.
Aerosol optical depth (AOD) at 550nm from Sunphotometer measurements from Aerosol Robotic Network (AERONET) are used as reference to satellite retrieved reanalysis and the global climate models. AOD satellite reanalysis data from the MERRA2 are used with analogous aerosol properties from Historical Phase 6 of the CMIP6 model runs. The CMIP6 includes 33 participating model groups (Eyring et al., 2016) and data is available through the CMIP6 search interface https://esgf-data.dkrz.de/search/cmip6-dkrz/. Of these 33 models, I focus on ten models to evaluate the AOD. The model specifications can be found in Table 1.

AERONET Sunphotometer¶

I want to read in the AOD measrued at 550nm by the Sunphotometer for the Arctic region. The Arctic region is defined as latitudes larger than 66$^\circ$ N. I will transform it to xarry, since its functionality will make it easier for me to handle the data. Plotting is similar as in pandas. The function read_aerocom_return_xarray_median_std will help me to read in the ungridded data with Pyaerocom. The output will give the AOD at 550nm, the longitude and latitude, median and standard deviation for the Arctic stations. Most of the stations had a course data coverage therfore did I decide to use the years 2006 to 2014.

MERRA2¶

In Section 3.1 the MERRA2 satellite reanalysis is evaluated against the ground-based AOD measurements to know how representative MERRA2 is for the Arctic stations. For this we used NASAs GIOVANNI interface to retrieve the monthly AOD averages for the stations. We chose the gridbox closes to the latitude and longitude of the AERONET stations in the Arctic.

The function read_merra2_return_xarray_median_std will read in the .csv files according to the station latitude and longitude from AERONET and returns a xarray. A monthly median and standard deviation is created for the AOD values to analyse the seasonal variability in Fig. 2 for 2006-2014.

In [5]:
# MERRA2 AOD values from Arctic stations
_mfile = merra_path + 'g4.areaAvgTimeSeries.M2IMNXGAS_5_12_4_AODANA.2006'
merra_arctic = fct.read_merra2_return_xarray_median_std(aeronet_arctic, _mfile, starty, endy)

MERRA2 satellite reananlysis has monthly averages of AOD from 1980. This values will be used to evaluate the CMIP6 historical simulations for the Arctic region (latitudes larger than 66$^\circ$N). The historical simulations help to evaluate the performance of the models against observations and futurer predictions. The function read_merra2 will return a pandas DataFrame.

After returning all CMIP models I will now search in the subfolders containing the AOD at 550nm. For each model, monthly data from 1980 - 2014 is chosen to overlap with MERRA2. There are several ensembles and run variations available. I use the r1i1p1f1, r1i1p2f1, r1i1p1f2 esnemble member, as it was available on the shared-cmip6-for-ns1000k folder.

Read all CMIP6 historical simulation including the AOD at 550nm (1980-2014) with read_all_cmip6_od550aer. The function will return a dictionary containing the model name and ensemble member. The longitude will be shifted from originally 0-360$^\circ$ to 180$^\circ$W - 180$^\circ$E. Areacella values are added to the xarray to later calculate the weighted averages with the masked_average function (provided by assistants on NEGI-2019 webpage).

In this step the weighted avarages for each CMIP6 model and ensemble member is performed for chosen years and chosen region. First I will evaluate the CMIP6 models in the Arctic region (latitude larger than 66$^\circ$N) between 1980 and 2014. The function calc_weighted_av_median_std will add to the existing cmip dictionary the weighted average for AOD as well as the monthly median and standard deviation for the chosen time period.

Results and Discussion¶

As mentioned before will CMIP6 historical simulations be evaluated against the satellite reanalysis product MERRA2. To have confidence in the analysis the MERRA2 AODs are compared to the AERONET ground-based stations Section 3.1. With a warming climate the areas of open water will increase in the Arctic. Related to this will the sea-salt and organic aerosol discharge increase (Glantz et al., 2014). The Arctic undergoes a seasonal cycle of AOD. During the Arctic summer new particles formation occurs due to higher insolation $\rightarrow$ higher levels of OH and more efficient precipitation cleansing. Section 3.2 will evaluate the CMIP6 seasonal cycle in the Arctic region between 1980 and 2014. A zonal assesement of CMIP6 models will then give an insight in how the models simulated the past three decades in a 'global' scale (Section 3.3).

MERRA2 evaluation¶

Seasonal AOD from the AERONET stations are compared to the MERRA2 reanalysis from 2006 to 2014 to determine how representative the fine resolution MERRA2 data is for the Arctic region.

Fig. 1: Monthly median for AOD at 550nm for 2006-2014. a) Aeronet stations above 66$^\circ$N. b)Aeronet Sunphotometer vs. MERRA2 for Arctic stations in corresponding colors. c) area averaged AOD for the Arctic region (180W-180E, 66-90N) vs. MERRA2 AOD at station gridbox.

In Fig. 1a) we see valid measurement stations for AOD in the Arctic region between 2006 and 2014. The monthly medians of AOD at the stations are presented in Fig. 1b). MERRA2 comparison on how well the AOD at the stations is in comparison to the Arctic area averaged AOD is shown in Fig. 1c). In Fig. 1b) is the linear Pearson correlation coefficient for for all stations +0.3, meaning the data points are varying from the best fit and having a medium correlation. We also see, that MERRA2 overestimates the monthly mean AOD. With this in mind we compare the two MERRA2 data sets Fig. 1c). The correlation is large (R$_{Pearson}$ = 0.7), but not best. However this result will give as later some confidence when we are analysing the CMIP6 historical simulations.

We want to see further how well the MERRA2 Arctic mean compares to the AERONET ground-based measurements, in particular the seasonal variation of AOD. Therefore monthly means for each station are plotted together with the MERRA2 data described in Section 2.2.

Fig. 2: Monthly median for AOD at 550nm between 2006-2014. Colored lines from the AERONET Sunphotometer at the station, blue: MERRA2 taken closest gridpoint to AERONET station, black: Arctic average.

The colored lines in Fig. 2 represent the monthly means from the AERONET stations between 2006 and 2014. Most of the ground-based observations show a AOD peak during spring, except Andenes (Norway) and Sodankyla (Finnland). Abisko (Sweden), Barrow (Alaska), Hornsund (Svalbard) and Ittoqqortoormiit (Greenland) show a second peak during Arctic summer.

Besides at the PEARL station (Northern Canda), none of the MERRA2 station data represents the seasonal cycle well. In all cases is the satellite reanalysis too high in comparison to the ground-based measurements.

MERRA2 station AOD averages are lower compared to the Arctic average for 50% of the stations, namely Abisko (Sweden), Hornsund (Svalbard), Ittoqqortoormiit (Greenland), Kangerlussuaq (Greenland), Ny Ålesund (Svalbard), OPAL, PEARL (Northern Canada), Thule (Greenland).

In all cases we have to keep in mind, that AOD can only be measured during Arctic summer and on cloud free days.

CMIP6 seasonal evaluation¶

The previous finding will be helpful for the assessment of the CMIP6 historical simulations between 1980 and 2014. We have to keep in mind, that the seasonal variation of AOD for the Arctic region is only partly representative for the AERONET stations. Furthermore, the MERRA2 AOD at 550nm is always too high when compared to the ground-based observations.

fct.plt_seasonal_model_ensemble(merra_arctic['M_Arctic'], ax,  starty, endy,'k' )
# plot CMIP6 seasonal cycle
for model, rea, i in zip(_mm, _rr, range(len(_mm))):
    # print(model,rea, i)
    valid_cmip[model][rea]['median_'+starty+endy].plot(ax = ax, 
                                                               label=model+'_'+rea,
                                                               color = sns.color_palette("hls",12)[i],
                                                               linewidth=3, 
                                                               linestyle='--')
    ax.fill_between(valid_cmip[model][rea]['median_'+starty+endy].month,
                            valid_cmip[model][rea]['median_'+starty+endy] - valid_cmip[model][rea]['std_'+starty+endy],
                            valid_cmip[model][rea]['median_'+starty+endy] + valid_cmip[model][rea]['std_'+starty+endy],
                            alpha=0.3,
                            facecolor=sns.color_palette("hls",12)[i])
    
ax.set_ylabel('AOD (550nm)')
ax.set_xlabel('%s - %s' %(starty,endy) )
ax.set_xlim([1,12])
ax.set_xticks(np.arange(1,13))
ax.set_xticklabels(['January', 'February', 'March', 'April', 'May', 'June', 'July', 'August', 'September', 'October', 'November', 'December'],
                   rotation = 45)
ax.set_title(' %sW - %sE, %sN - %sN, median and $\sigma$' %(lower_lon,upper_lon,lower_lat,upper_lat))
ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.1, 1.05));
Fig. 3: Monthly median for AOD at 550nm for the Arctic reagion between 1980-2014.

Fig. 3: shows the monthly mean averages for AOD in the Arctic region between 1980-2014. The black line indicates the MERRA2 reanalysis with its variability in grey shading. As expected is the uncertainty largest in the Arctic winter during polar night. Since AOD is measured optically it is not possible for the satellites to retrieve the AOD at 550nm during Arctic winter. I would look into detail how MERRA2 retrieves the winter AOD from the Arctic and compare it with the intial conditions if I would continue to study on this project. It also has to be taken into account, that AOD cannot be retrieved for cloudy days cloudy gridcells, and over snow/ice ground for MERRA2.

We see in Fig. 2: a seasonal variation of AOD at the stations and for MERRA2 data. A peak of AOD can not be seen for MERRA2 over a longer time period in Fig. 3:. One reason can be that the not existing peak for the stations in the American Arctic during spring counterparts the European Arctic AOD peak.

The coloured lines show the AODs from the CMIP6 model medians and their uncertainty. One CMIP6 model, namely CanESM5 (green) catches ones eye. It simulates a distinct peak of AOD with large variability during Arctic spring for the 1980 -2014 averages. On the other hand is the CanESM5 too low during summer and not within the MERRA2 variability. The GFDL-ESM4 model (cyan) is within the MERRA2 variability in the winter month (September – March), but again too low during summer.

Glantz et al., 2014 studied the previous version of NorESM2-LM by validating it with MODIS satellite AOD measurements. The NorESM CMIP5 model showed then too low values for AOD at 550nm. In Fig. 3: we can see, that NorESM-LM (yellow) is almost constant over the course of the year.

CMIP6 zonal evaluation¶

The impact of anthropogenic emission can also be seen zonally.

Fig. 4: Zonal average of AOD for last three decades, 1980-1989, 1990 - 1999 and 2000 - 2009. a): MERRA2, b): CanESM5, c): GFDL-ESM4 and d): NorESM2-LM zonal averages for each decade. The black line in b - d) is the MERRA2 zonal mean for 2000 - 2009.

Fig. 4a) shows the MERRA2 zonally averaged AOD for three decades, 1980s, 1990s and 2000s. Around 60$^\circ$S we see the AOD dominated by sea salt, in the Tropics (15$^\circ$N) the influence by Sahran dust and the midlatitudes in the Northern Hemisphere influence by biogass burning and anthropogenic emissions. Especially in the Northern Hemisphere we see a decrease of AOD (compare 1980s to 2000s). Fig. 4b-c) show the MERRA2 zonally average from 2000s and the three CMIP6 models, CanESM5, GFDL-ESM4 and NorESM-LM. We see that the historical simulations in all three models do not vary a lot over the three decades.

CanESM5 simulates too low AOD in the tropics and subtropics and too high AOD in midlatitudes of the Northern Hemisphere. Compared to MERRA2 has CanESM5 a shifted AOD peak, instead at 15$^\circ$N at 40$^\circ$N. It agrees with the decedal trend seen with MERRA2, namely a decrease of AOD in the Northern Hemisphere. GFDL-ESM4 seems to agree along all latitudes and is within the MERRA2 uncertainty (Here I have to add the uncertainy in the plots will be done for final). But too little AOD in the Arctic and too high AOD (production of too much sea salt?) in the Southern Hemisphere at 50$^\circ$S. NorESM-LM does not follow any zonal pattern reanalysed by MERRA2. NorESM-LM has high AOD values in the Southern Hemisphere producing too much sea salt. But further studies should be carried out to find the reason for the high sea salt around 60$^\circ$S (see also Sofies work on the sea salt observation model comparison for the Arctic). On the other hand, the AOD in the Northern Hemisphere do not agree at all with the MERRA2 reanalysis. Too little AOD is simulated for all three decades.

Summary and Conclusion¶

In this project I analysed how representative the MERRA2 satellite reanalysis is in comparison to the ground-based AOD Sunphotometers for Arctic stations. I used this further to see how representative the MERRA2 Arctic AOD average is. This helped me to do a seasonal intercomparison to 12 CMIP6 models with respect to MERRA2 for the Arctic region during 1980 – 2014. I chose three CMIP6 models (CanESM5, GFDL-ESM4 and NorESM2-LM) to analyse the decadel change of zonal AOD since 1980. In general overestimates MERRA2 the AOD. Seasonal variation of Arctic AOD were mostly not seen by the MERRA2 data. Sunphotometer observations are barely within the MERRA2 uncertainty and further analysis has to be done to understand the higher values of MERRA2. The largest uncertainty of MERRA2 Arctic AOD mean were seen in during the Arcti winter. For 1980-2014 averages was no destinct spring AOD peak seen from the MERRA2 data set, but it showed in the monthly averages of 2006-2014. The seasonal variation for monthly AOD average were mostly not reproduced by the CMIP6 models, as already seen in CMIP5. Only the CanESM5 is within the range of MERRA2 during spring, but on the other side too low in the summer time. GFDL-ESM4s is within the MERRA2 uncertainty during winter and has a weak seasonal pattern. The is no variation of the monthly means for NorESM-LM. Zonally fit the GFDL-ESM4 model the best over all three decades. CanESM5 reproduced the AOD pattern along the latitude, but the AOD peak in the subtropics is shifted towards North. For all three decades is the CanESM5 in good agreement with the MERRA2 decadal reanalysis. NorESM2-LM does not reproduce the AOD zonal averages as it is seen by MERRA2. It produces too high sea salt in the Souther Hemisphere and too little AOD above 60$^\circ$N.

Further studies have to be carried out, especially a detailed study of AOD in NorESM to understand the high and low values above 50$^\circ$N and south.
